{
  "texts": [
    "Teachers designed tools tailored for their classrooms, such as, a socio-emotional learning tool, a language learning through AI character personality design, and a social justice art reflection tool to promote creative inquiry.",
    "A thematic analysis of pedagogical practices emerging in teachers' lessons revealed the use of reflective practice, inquirybased learning, iterative learning, representation of self, project-based learning, ethical reflection in art making, aesthetic and emotional management (see Figure 2).",
    "While discussing implications of AI tools in the classroom, teachers were most concerned about the over-reliance on AI and impact on students' critical thinking, data privacy, and were most hopeful for AI's ability to offer personalized learning and student support, support students' creativity and innovation, and their skill development for the future.",
    "In this work we suggest a three stage approach -learning about AI, using AI tools in lessons, and developing AI tools for their own classrooms, that involves educators as key stakeholders in designing learning materials and tools, and empowers them to be informed users, creators and educators in an AI-driven future.",
    "Meaningfully including educators is an effective medium of making AI learning accessible to non-technical classrooms and adapt to diverse pedagogies."
  ]
}